post_text:
**DON'T FORGET!!**

TOMORROW, Tuesday, September 8th, Rome City Schools will be participating in a Flexible Learning Day!

Flexible Learning Day is an opportunity for students to continue their learning at home with a variety of options that include digital resources, paper and pencil assignments and hands-on activities while teachers participate in Professional Learning Communities.

Teachers at every school will provide short, grade-appropriate lessons for each student to enrich standards introduced in class. Assignments will not contain new material or subject matter; they will serve as practice or extension of the standards.

In addition, because Flexible Learning Days are considered an instructional day for students, they can be used in a variety of scenarios, such as inclement weather or parent conference days.

Track at Barron Stadium Re-Open to Public on Wednesday, September 9

ROME, GA— Rome City Schools is excited to announce the re-opening of the track at Barron Stadium beginning on Wednesday, September 9th.

We ask that all guests please refrain from using the turf and entering the bleachers during your visit, as the stands will be taped off in order to ensure they stay clean and ready for the next event. If you plan to use the facilities, we ask that all abide by the established rules and regulations in order to help keep Barron Stadium in great condition.

Also note that the stadium will be closed the day before any scheduled event to ensure that RCS staff has ample time to sanitize the facilities before use.

We are excited to welcome the public back to use Barron Stadium’s track and we look forward to enjoying this space on Friday night’s in support of our Wolves!

Rome City Schools recently applied and was selected to participate in the use of the MTSS/SST application pilot program!

The purpose of the Georgia Online MTSS/SST Application is to help districts and schools create, monitor, update and maintain a record of a student's response to interventions. Georgia is currently using this application for students receiving Tier III support and interventions.

To learn more about GO MSST/SST, visit their website: https://www.gadoe.org/Curriculum-Instruction-and-Assessment/Special-Education-Services/Pages/TieredSystemofSupports.aspx

Go Wolves!

post_text:
Congratulations to Rome High School student, Cristian Fonseca, on his commitment to play soccer at the University of Maine at Presque Isle!

Fonseca is a striker for the Wolves and a ten year member of the Rome Aresnal Soccer Club where he has excelled as one of the top strikers in the State.

According to a press release written by the University of Maine at Presque Isle, during his four years on Rome High's varsity team, Fonseca was twice selected 1st Team All-Region and during his senior season was named to the 2020 Southeast All-American team that included the top players from Georgia, Texas, Florida and South Carolina. During Fonseca's senior season he was the Co-Leader in goals scored for the entire State of Georgia with 18.

Congratulations to Cristian for this awesome accomplishment!

To read the official press release, visit their website at: http://owls.umpi.edu/sports/msoc/2020-21/releases/20200831njxf51

GO WOLVES!

Rome High School Volleyball Senior Night: Lauren Davis

ROME, GA— During Rome High’s two matches against the Rockmart Yellowjackets and the Murray County Indians on Friday, August 28, the Lady Wolves took the time to celebrate the class of 2021 and recognize the seniors who have dedicated themselves to Rome High’s volleyball program.

Lauren Davis is a senior captain for the Lady Wolves and has served her team as a defensive specialist.

Her favorite volleyball memory is when she got a dig against a D1 hitter on the 10-foot line.

Davis plans to attend Berry College to study Psychology and minor in biblical and Christian studies.

GO WOLVES!

Rome Wolves Football Ticket Info

ROME, GA— If you are fired up about watching our Wolves take on the Rockmart Yellow Jackets this Friday, Sept. 4th, then you are in luck!

Tickets are now on sale and can be purchased using this link: https://gofan.co/app/school/GA5278

Please be advised, seating capacity has been reduced to ensure physical distancing guidelines can be observed during the game. The option to purchase tickets will be available in-person at the ticket booth on the day of the game until the stadium reaches safe capacity numbers.

If you wish to purchase tickets at the gate on gameday, please be advised that volunteers will only take cash for the purchase of tickets.

If you wish to reserve your seat, it is advised to purchase tickets in advance using the link above.

As always, we appreciate your support of our students and we look forward to cheering on our band, cheerleaders, and our football team, their support team and their coaches!!!

Go Wolves!!!

post_text:
*ATTENTION ALL!

The announcement below contains an application available to ALL RCS FAMILIES who have children that were enrolled in RCS schools during the shutdown due to COVID-19 this past year.

Rome City Schools is a CEP district, therefore all students should be eligible to receive this benefit.

Each child qualifies for $256.50 to use for food, and the funds will be available via an EBT card issued by the Department of Family and Children Services.

The application is easy to complete! Parents can obtain their student's GT-ID number from the school where they were enrolled from March until May of 2020.

Again, this program is available to ALL RCS FAMILIES and all students should be eligible for use as RCS is a CEP district. We encourage you to take advantage of this opportunity!

See the announcement below for more information.

Rome High School Varsity Football to Start in Fall

ROME, GA—The Georgia High School Association has approved a two-week delay to the 2020 high school football season. Our Rome Wolves have been hard at work in preparation for this year’s first kickoff scheduled for September 4, 2020 at Historic Barron Stadium.

Head Football Coach and Athletic Director for Rome City Schools, John Reid, is excited for the season to get underway. He and his coaching staff have been taking care of play on the field, while RCS administrators are planning and developing procedures for keeping fans healthy and safe during the games.

Fear not, Rome Football fans. Friday Night Lights will shine again this fall!

Go Wolves!!!

Rome City Schools to Host 2020 Graduation Photo Opportunity

In lieu of a formal graduation ceremony, Rome City Schools will be hosting a photo opportunity for those 2020 graduates who wish to participate.

The photo opportunity will be held at Barron Stadium on Saturday, July 18 from 8:00 a.m. until 4:00 p.m.

Each graduate that wishes to participate must sign up for a time using this link: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/60b094aafae2ca0fe3-graduation1. We also ask that each family bring their own camera for photos.

Social distancing requirements will be in effect, and each person will be required to wear a mask/ face covering, which can be removed for the photograph.

Gowns will need to be returned at the Rome High bus ramp on July 20th between 9:00 a.m. and 12:00 p.m.

GO WOLVES! #1Rome #OWNIT

post_text:
Gabriel Pineda has signed and committed to Shorter University! He will continue his athletic and academic career at the highly prestigious where he plans to major in Business.

Gabriel has played soccer since he was in second grade and has played for Rome High School for the past four years. When asked about his overall experience, Gabriel claimed that the road was long and tough. He had to fight the whole way during his career and even had to fight to earn the right to be the varsity team captain.

He is very excited to continue his soccer career at Shorter and looks forward to competing for playing time and a starting role next season. Gabriel’s favorite soccer player and inspiration is Lionel Messi. The advice he gave for future soccer players of Rome High was simple.“Keep working hard, and never stop pursuing your dream," he said.

Congratulations, Gabriel!

Bottom row: Ludy Morales, Gabriel Pineda, Juan Pineda
Top row: Elliot Cousins, Luis Goya, and Joseph Hastings

4 Rome High Graduates receive an Alpha Kappa Alpha Scholarship

The local chapter of the Alpha Kappa Alpha Sorority has awarded an academic scholarship to four of Rome High’s Class of 2020 Seniors, Kelsey Beeman, Cydney Freeman, Amberly Brown, and Aaron Bailey.

A stringent list of criteria, including GPA and character, must be met to achieve the scholarship, and Rome High School 12th Grade Counselor says these students meet them all and more. “They are all such people of character who lead by example, displays a strong work ethic, and always has a positive attitude,” says Ms. Eidson. “All four will be excellent ambassadors for Rome High School as they continue their educational journey.”

The contestant talent was only judged.

We are proud to announce the 2nd place winner, our very own, Charlie Shane. He is a Rome High School 11th Grade student.

Piano Solo
Excursions Op. 20
Samuel Barber

post_text:
A message from Quincy Nation: Kindergarten Teacher and K-2 SST Coordinator at West Central Elementary:

I have taught kindergarten at West Central for 14 years. About 8 years ago, I began going through my class photos at the end of each year to find pictures of the graduating 6th-grade students that I taught. I make copies for them and invite the 6th graders to visit my classroom during the last week of school. They always have fun reminiscing about their days in kindergarten, and I really get a kick out of what they remember about being in my class. I'm sad that I won't be able to have that reunion with this year's 6th graders. So, I made this little video that includes pictures from their first day of kindergarten and our yearbook page from the 2013-2014 school year. I am so proud of these students and wish them all the best in middle school next year and beyond! #leadersofthepack

post_text:
From Ashley Chastain: Kindergarten Teacher at West Central Elementary School

To my students: I want you to always know this year was one of the best years, and I will always remember you all because this was my first group of kiddos to teach! Just know I miss you all so much. It’s difficult to know what the future holds, so remember that before anything else, I love you and care about you. I wish I could hug you all and say goodbye, but this is not the end of our story together. #leadersofthepack

post_text:
Knowledge at Night

If you’re up tonight, you may be able to catch a glimpse of the biggest and brightest moon of 2020.

Sarah Brown, Astronomy Teacher for Rome High School, shared:

“Bringing us a literal silver lining in these dark times is the night sky’s brightest object of 2020, the Pink Supermoon. Named such for a pink flower blooming in the spring (and not indicative of the moon’s color), the pink supermoon will be most easily visible between 10:30 pm and midnight tonight, April 7th. Tonight’s moon is called a supermoon because the moon is near perigee, its closest point to Earth. As such, it can appear approximately 30% brighter than when it is at its farthest point. Take a moment tonight to wander outside for some night-sky viewing!”

post_text:
World Health Day is a global health awareness day celebrated every year on April 7th.

As we all continue to navigate COVID-19, let’s do our part in adhering to the guidelines per the CDC:

-Social Distancing

-Wash your hands with soap and water for 20 seconds.

-Cover coughs or sneeze with a tissue.

-Avoid touching your eyes, nose, and mouth.

-Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.

__________________________________________________________

El Día Mundial de la Salud es un día mundial de concientización sobre la salud que se celebra cada año el 7 de abril.

Mientras todos seguimos navegando por COVID-19, hagamos nuestra parte para cumplir con las pautas de los CDC:

-Distanciamiento social

-Lávate las manos con agua y jabón durante 20 segundos.

-Cover tos o estornudar con un pañuelo de papel.

-Evitar tocarse los ojos, la nariz y la boca.

-Limpie y desinfecte los objetos y superficies que se tocan con frecuencia con un spray o toallita de limpieza doméstica.

Based on the Executive Order of Governor Brian Kemp, Rome City Schools will adhere to the mandate to remain closed for in-person instruction for the remainder of the 2019 / 2020 school year.

We will continue the Flexible Learning Plan for the remainder of the school year.

Additional information will be forth coming.

Hi!

My name is Miss Regina Evans. I am a first year teacher at Rome Middle (Shorter University Class of 2019). This year, I am teaching 8th grade math.

Throughout my college career, my education professors kept saying teachers should be "flexible" because we do not know what is going to happen. This Coronavirus outbreak is an example of "flexibility" being important. ("Flexibility" meaning being able to change instruction and lessons 'on the spot'.)

I wanted to share with you what my son is doing during his time at home. His name is Seth and he’s in 8th grade at Rome Middle. He’s started a garden in our backyard to help our family out with food that we eat on a daily basis. He’s working extra hard and he’s learning so much along the way! I’m very proud of him for wanting to do this. I know the reward will be very fulfilling for him!

post_text:
A really cute video from Main Elementary Kindergarten Teacher Katie Farrar:

I teach Kindergarten and have awesome students! I write a lot about my cat, Houdini, during Writer’s Workshop. My class loves hearing about him, so I thought they’d love to see him in a video! We are really into the Flat Stanley book series!! I’m going to start reading a chapter at a time on my YouTube channel. I hope my students are reading a lot and working on their math skills. I also hope that they stay safe in the chaotic situation that we are trying to navigate through together (but from a distance). #leadersofthepack

post_text:
A message from Merrimac Forsyth:

I teach 4th math at Elm Street. I have around 76 students from gifted to Special Education. I teach regular, ESOL, EIP. My students and I have a great rapport. I try to be enthusiastic, positive, and caring in the classroom; therefore, I thought sending the videos out would help my students on a daily basis. They would know that I was still their teacher even if it was from a far. The coaches made a RCS math assignment so I made videos that explained the assignments. I walked through each slide without giving the answers. The first video was a review of Place Value. #leadersofthepack

post_text:
An encouraging message West End Elementary Teacher Ginger Jarrell:

I teach Kindergarten and some of my former students are graduates this year and I just wanted to make the video because it makes me so proud to have graduated from a school system who has truly banded together in a time like this. We did not anticipate something like this, but this whole system (from the administrators to the teachers and staff to the students and even to the parents), everyone has come together and I have seen motivational comments, amazing learning, feeding students and major adjustments/shifts to accommodate each other as best we can. We are taking the "All in" challenge to an extreme in a good way! We are super fantastic and I LOVE IT! #leadersofthepack

post_text:
LEADER OF THE PACK - Bethany Segal

I teach Kindergarten at Main Elementary. I have 13 hardworking children who enjoy learning new things. We work hard on our sight words and we do activities all day related to learning them. My students love to "show what they know" and give a thumbs-up whenever they see or hear one of our sight words. We love to dance and sing, which I try to incorporate as much as possible. We've come up with some motions and dances that help us remember our long and short vowel sounds! #leadersofthepack

post_text:
Some encouraging words from one of our "LEADERS OF THE PACK" Jessica Alexander:

I teach first grade at Anna K. Davie, I have 20 awesome students in my class. My class takes time everyday at school to read & I try to encourage them to make reading fun. Every Friday we do “flashlight Friday” where we turn off the lights and read with flashlights, I also use flexible seating, partner reading and fun witch pointer fingers for tracking to make reading fun for them. On Thursday and Fridays we do response to reading during writing time where they write a response to a book.

post_text:
Rome City Schools Actividades escolares | Miércoles, 03.11.20

Después de considerar la información más reciente que nos proporcionó el Departamento de Salud de Georgia, las Escuelas de la Ciudad de Roma desearían aprovechar esta oportunidad para compartir que en este momento, todas las actividades planificadas de la Escuela de la Ciudad de Roma se llevarán a cabo según lo programado.

Si un padre decide no permitir que su hijo participe, no será penalizado.

Continuaremos colaborando, compartiendo información y monitoreando la situación con los funcionarios de salud locales y estatales para ayudar a proteger nuestras comunidades escolares.

Si se toma la decisión de cancelar o posponer una actividad, las actualizaciones se publicarán en el sitio web de nuestro distrito, en los canales de redes sociales y en las familias a través de nuestros sistemas de notificación masiva.

Gracias por su apoyo y comprensión mientras continuamos revisando esta situación en curso.

Rome City Schools School Activities | Wednesday, 03.11.20

After considering the most recent information provided to us by the Georgia Department of Health, Rome City Schools would like to take this opportunity to share that at the present time, all planned Rome City School activities will take place as scheduled.

If a parent chooses not to allow his or her child to participate, he or she will not be penalized.

We will continue to collaborate, share information, and monitor the situation with local and state health officials to help protect our school communities.

If a decision is made that an activity is cancelled / postponed updates will be posted on our district website, social media channels, and to families through our mass notification systems.

Thank you for your support and understanding as we continue to review this ongoing situation.

Several Rome High School and Rome Middle School students were selected to participate in the Georgia Music Educators Association All-State Chorus Festival for the 2019- 2020 school year.

These students worked extremely hard to be selected to participate in this event by passing through a rigorous audition process. Over 5,000 students in the State of Georgia auditioned for All-State Chorus this year, and only about 1,500 students grades 7-12 were selected to participate.

Rome City Schools would like to recognize these students for their accomplishments!

Rome High Students- Carson Garrett, Mallory Rogers, Abby Hart, and Josh Hart.

Rome Middle School students- Sam Thomas and Joseph Lee.

March 4 at 4:28 PM ·

Rome High School Girls Soccer Dominates East Paulding 6-0

ROME, GA— The Rome High School Lady Wolves dominated East Paulding, 6-0, during last night’s varsity soccer game held at Barron Stadium.

Rome’s Mae Pierce scored two of the six goals, with one assist. Joey Kunczewski, Janet Hartman and Allyson Harris also scored one goal, followed by Jennifer Zavala who scored one goal and had one assist. Grace Buck played a half in goal, securing the Wolves’ win.

“I am very proud of how we played last night. I think we did really well,” said Jessica Hewitt, Head Coach for the Lady Wolves. “The girls are working hard at practice and in games, and it is most definitely showing. At practice, we have been focusing on playing simple and working together. I hope we can keep that up for our next game on Thursday against Darlington.”

The Lady Wolves will host the Tigers at Barron Stadium on Thursday, March 5, starting at 5:30 p.m.

Senior Night festivities will take place on Tuesday, March 10 at 5:30 p.m. during the game against Woodland High School.

GO WOLVES!

February 26 at 10:03 PM ·

Anna K. Davie Celebrates African Americans and the Arts!!!

Educators and students at AKD gave a nod to the past with a special Black History presentation at the school.

Students dressed as influential African Americans and offered the crowd information about their contributions to Black History. From dance numbers to poems recited by the students, attendees were offered an experience that gave them an overall idea of how Black History is such a large part of who we all are today.

Guests were also treated to soul food-inspired dishes in the school cafeteria after the event.

Please enjoy these photos from the night's festivities!

Go Wolves!

Nathan Medley, Rome High Freshman standout swimmer, selected second team All-State for his performance in the 200 yard freestyle event!!!

Medley had a record-setting season as a freshman making state cuts in seven out of eight individual swimming events. Only one other swimmer in the history of Rome High School has qualified for that many events in one season. Medley also broke two Rome High swimming records in the 200 freestyle (1:45.23) and 500 freestyle (4:52.59) events.

At this year's state meet, Medley came in fourth place in 200 freestyle and fifth in the 500 freestyle. He was the fastest freshman in both events.

Congratulations, Nathan!!! We are so proud of you!!!

Go Wolves!!!

#RHSallstateswimmer

Mayor Bill Collins Visits West End

ROME, GA— Rome Mayor, Bill Collins, stopped by West End Elementary School to speak with students about his ties to Rome and how he became interested in local politics.

"We are so grateful to Mayor Bill Collins for his recent visit to West End Elementary," said Dr. Dennis Drummond, Principal for West End. "Our second graders learned so much from his presentation about the importance of local government."
